ry James, Tolstoy, and Edith Wharton. The first half of the work concentrates on social morality, establishing the conditions all good lives must meet. The second discusses personal morality, the sphere of individuality. Its development enables us to discover what is important to us and how we can fit our personal aspirations into the forms of life our moral tradition provides. Kekes's argument derives its inspiration from Aristotle's objectivism, Hume's emphasis on custom and feeling, and Mill's concentration on individuals and their experiments in living. This book is a nontechnical yet closely reasoned attempt to provide a contemporary answer to the age-old question of how to live well.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAnnas, Julia.  aAristotle.  aBerlin, Isaiah.  aBrookner, Anita.  aCallisthenes.  aFingarette, Herbert.  aFoot, Philippa.  aJames, Henry.  aKantianism.  aKnox, Bernard.  aappeal.  aautonomy.  abenevolence.  abreadth.  acivic friendship.  acoherence.  acomplex moral situations.  aconservatism.  aconventions.  adefeasible commitments.  adouble-mindedness.  aenforcement of social morality.  aexternal goods.  agood and evil.  agood judgment.  ahappiness.  ahuman limitations.  ahuman welfare.  aincommensurability.  aintegrity.  ainterpretation.  alatitude.  aliberalism.  aloose commitments.  amodern sensibility.  amoral horror.  anaturalism.  aobjectivism.  aobjectivity.  aperfection.  apersonal satisfaction.  apluralism.  aprinciples.  arealism.  areflective purity.  aself-condemnation.  asimple moral situations.  asympathy.  atests of good lives.  autilitarianism.  avirtues.  avoluntarism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-